{
  "text": "Using purposive sampling methods, I chose women who were married, Caucasian, and residing in the Midwest. This was purely a means to narrow the diversity of my sample to allow for greater depth of inquiry and not a personal reflection that Caucasian, married women are typical or normative types of mothers. I started with a convenience sample of women known to me who fit the identified criteria and then asked participants if they knew other women who might be interested in being interviewed for this study. This is known as snowballing sampling [CITATION_1] .",
  "citation_candidates": [
